## Why This Week Matters

The two supply-chain attack campaigns disclosed this week are not theoretical — they are actively exfiltrating credentials from organizations right now, and the blast radius extends well beyond developers: stolen cloud keys and CI/CD secrets can open the door to your entire cloud infrastructure. At the same time, a disclosed Exchange Server vulnerability and a hard platform retirement deadline create time-sensitive operational decisions that cannot wait for the next planning cycle.

The broader context is that AI agent adoption has crossed from experimentation into production across Microsoft's platform simultaneously — Agent 365, computer-using agents in Copilot Studio, and new identity governance controls for agents all went generally available in the same window. The one thing leadership must understand: **the governance infrastructure for AI agents now exists; the organizational risk is in deploying agents without using it.**

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog — What's New in Security May 2026](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/05/21/whats-new-in-microsoft-security-may-2026/) · [Microsoft Entra Blog — Agent Sprawl Governance](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-entra-blog/get-ahead-of-agent-sprawl-manage-and-govern-ai-agents-at-scale/ba-p/4513160) · [Microsoft Agent 365 GA Announcement](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/05/01/microsoft-agent-365-now-generally-available-expands-capabilities-and-integrations/)*

