## What Your Employees Will Notice

- **Microsoft 365 Copilot has a new design.** The Copilot app and its integration across Word, Excel, PowerPoint, and Teams has been visually refreshed — cleaner layout, faster access, more prominent in the flow of work. Expect questions about the new interface.
- **New AI models in Copilot.** Anthropic Claude Opus 4.8 and GPT-5.5 Instant are now available in Copilot Chat, Excel, PowerPoint, and Copilot Studio. Users may notice different response styles depending on which model Copilot selects for a given task.
- **Copilot Notebooks now connects to meetings and email.** Users can add Teams meeting transcripts and Outlook emails as knowledge sources in Copilot Notebooks, enabling richer project workspaces. Rolling out in preview for June/July — communicate proactively so employees understand what data is being referenced.
- **Teams Live Events: last call.** Employees who organize or attend Live Events should be notified that scheduling ends June 30. Direct them to the new Teams events experience for future planning.
- **Teams call transfers are faster.** A streamlined call transfer workflow in Teams Phone reduces the steps required and suggests transfer targets — a welcome quality-of-life improvement for call-heavy roles.
- **Teams inline search in the compose box.** Employees can now use @mentions to search for files, chats, channels, and meetings directly while composing a message, without switching contexts.
- **Word Legal Agent (Frontier).** Legal teams enrolled in the Frontier program will see a new Legal Agent in Word that can generate redlines and review counterparty changes. Proactive communication to Legal is recommended to set appropriate expectations about AI-assisted review.
- **Copilot voice chat now offers multiple voice styles.** Users can select from different voice options in Microsoft 365 Copilot voice experiences.

*Sources: [M365 Copilot Blog — What's New May 2026](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-365-copilot-blog/what-s-new-in-microsoft-365-copilot-may-2026/ba-p/4522010) · [Microsoft 365 Blog — New Copilot Design](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-365/blog/2026/05/28/introducing-a-new-design-for-microsoft-365-copilot/) · [Teams Blog — Live Events Retirement](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-teams-blog/retiring-teams-live-events-the-next-chapter-for-events-at-scale/ba-p/4486465)*

---

## What Your Help Desk Should Expect

- **Copilot interface confusion.** The refreshed Microsoft 365 Copilot design will generate "where did X go?" tickets. Prepare a brief one-pager or FAQ for first-line support covering the key navigation changes.
- **Teams Live Events migration requests.** Expect an uptick in requests from event organizers who discover they can no longer schedule Live Events after June 30. Help desk should be prepared to direct users to the new Teams events experience and escalate calendar conflicts for events already in flight.
- **"My email client stopped working" tickets.** As legacy TLS and older POP/IMAP configurations are deprecated, some shared mailboxes, automated processes, and older mobile devices will lose connectivity without warning. Prioritize proactive audit over reactive ticket resolution.
- **Copilot model questions.** Users may ask why Copilot "responds differently" or "uses a different model." Help desk should be briefed that multiple AI models (GPT-5.5, Claude Opus 4.8) are now available and Copilot selects based on task type — this is expected behavior.
- **Copilot Notebooks data source questions.** As meeting and email grounding rolls out, some users will ask what data Copilot can "see" in Notebooks. Help desk needs clear guidance on data boundaries and how to advise users appropriately.
- **macOS enrollment experience changes.** Platform SSO during Automated Device Enrollment for macOS is now GA, which may change the first-boot experience for newly enrolled Macs. Prepare IT staff for enrollment support questions if rolling out new Apple devices.
- **Exchange Server OWA questions.** If your organization runs on-premises Exchange, employees may receive communication about a mitigation being applied to OWA. Help desk should be ready to reassure users that this is a protective measure, not an outage.

*Sources: [Intune What's New — May 2026](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-intune-blog/what-s-new-in-microsoft-intune-may/ba-p/4491984) · [Entra Blog — Platform SSO macOS GA](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-entra-blog/platform-sso-during-automated-device-enrollment-is-now-generally/ba-p/4436813) · [Exchange Team Blog — Legacy TLS Deprecation](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/deprecating-legacy-tls-and-endpoints-for-pop-and-imap-in/ba-p/4515201)*

