## If You Take No Action

**On the active supply-chain credential theft campaigns:** Your software development and CI/CD infrastructure may already be compromised, and you would not know it. These campaigns execute silently during routine build operations — no user clicks required. Stolen cloud credentials (AWS, GitHub, Kubernetes) give attackers the keys to your production environment. Downstream consequences include ransomware deployment, data exfiltration triggering breach notification obligations, and cloud resource abuse that generates immediate financial cost. Your cyber insurance policy almost certainly requires reasonable security controls in build environments; a known active campaign with no response is a difficult position to defend in a claim.

**On CVE-2026-42897 (Exchange OWA vulnerability):** An unpatched on-premises Exchange server exposes every employee who reads email in OWA to potential session hijacking by a threat actor who can send them a single email. No user action beyond opening the message is required to trigger the vulnerability. For organizations in regulated industries, a compromised email system is a reportable incident under HIPAA, CMMC, and most state privacy laws. The longer this sits unmitigated, the broader the exposure window.

**On Teams Live Events retirement (June 30):** After June 30, no new Live Events can be scheduled. Organizations that rely on this format for employee town halls, all-hands meetings, or external broadcasts will discover the gap at exactly the wrong moment — typically when an event is already being planned or promoted. The new Teams events experience requires familiarization and may need IT configuration before it is ready for production use. Four weeks is sufficient time to act, but only if action begins now.

